Text: Decree 13, the Basic Constitution and Provisions Decree, were the statutes then. It provided the NEC with powers to disqualify a candidate or postpone the election. These documents also charged the NEC with the task of conducting the elections
Name: MOE da History Man (Not an Affidavit Story Teller)

Text: The National Electoral Commission (NEC) , was the body in charged with elections in Nigeria then with professor, Humphrey Nwosu, as its chairman.
Name: MOE da History Man (Not an Affidavit Story Teller)

Text: On 10 June 1993, the Federal High Court FCT served the NEC an injunction. The injuction restrained NEC from going on with the election scheduled for June 12 pending the settlement of a law suit instituted against the NEC by the Association for a Better Nigeria (ABN).
Name: MOE da History Man (Not an Affidavit Story Teller)

Text: Ignoring the court injunction of June 10, NEC went on to conduct the now popular June 12, 1993 election as scheduled. Relying on the powers of the decree 13 which set it up.
Name: MOE da History Man (Not an Affidavit Story Teller)

Text: Seeing the situation, the ABN approached the court again on June 15, 1993 and got an interim Order by an Abuja Court. The Order restrains NEC from releasing the results of the presidential elections.
Name: MOE da History Man (Not an Affidavit Story Teller)

Text: June 16, 1993, the NEC informed Nigerians that it had decided not release the final result of the presidential election held on June 12, 1993 until further notice due to ABN court actions and the injunction restraining it from announcing the results.
Name: MOE da History Man (Not an Affidavit Story Teller)

Text: 24 hours after June 17, 1993, a Lagos High Court reversed NEC's decision. It ordered that NEC should release the June 12 1993 presidential election results within 24 hours. Justice Moshood Olugbani was the Judge in this instance
Name: MOE da History Man (Not an Affidavit Story Teller)

Text: Seeing the intricacies,  Right groups started mobilising, there was serious suspicion. Campaign for Democracy (CD) was active. It issued ultimatum to the NEC to announce the election result or else it would regardless of NEC being the body statutorily positioned to do so
Name: MOE da History Man (Not an Affidavit Story Teller)

Text: By June 22 the NEC approached the Court of Appeal Kaduna to challenge the injunction by the Abuja High Court restraining it from announcing the presidential election result. But June 23, 1993 IBB announced to the nation, the annulment of the June 12, 1993 election
Name: MOE da History Man (Not an Affidavit Story Teller)
